lender.name: Kara
lender.loan_because:
I discovered Kiva on March 1, 2012, and I think it's amazing. While extremely sick and stuck in bed, I helped someone on the other side of the world buy hog feed, so he can keep breeding and selling them so he can feed his family.
The coolest thing is, it's not one of those 27¢ a day things, where the sad kid in the picture only gets about a nickel of it. It's a program that offers micro-loans (a few hundred dollars a piece, usually) to people in poverty who are trying to start/maintain some sort of work to support their families. Then, over six months to a year, they pay back the loans when they start to make a profit. So around July, my $25 dollars will have helped Reynaldo, and then will be back in my Kiva profile to lend to someone else, or to donate to keep Kiva running, (since they don't take any money at all out for themselves) or to put back into my bank account through PayPal.
I read all the logistics and fineprint, and as far as I can tell it's truly legitimate. The loan repayment rate is 98.91%! Isn't that amazing? That says to me that this program really helps these people, so much that they can pay back the people around the world who helped them get started.
And when you see the statistics, like that over $2M dollars were lent THIS WEEK ALONE; 31,103 people loaned money this week; 4,236 borrowers were fully funded this week.... It kind of restores my faith in humanity, you know?
I always talk about how I wish I could help more people, but I don't have the means to do it...Seeing all these people doing what I want to do...All those little $25 loans adding up to MILLIONS of dollars a week... It's beautiful.
Heck, I wish I'd thought of it, but I'm just happy to be a part of it. I can easily live without missing that $25 for six months, but for someone on the other side of the world, it's a small fortune that makes all the difference.
So while I was stuck in bed feeling worthless and frustrated, I found a way to help someone, even without being able to get out of bed and go somewhere to do it. That cheered me up a bit. I don't have very much money, but I don't need very much when thousands of other people can help a little bit, too. Thousands of little bits add up really quickly. :)
lender.occupational_info: I am an actor in Michigan film and theatre, as well as Director of Personnel for a local professional theatre company. I also design, create and sell jewelry. I have a line called "Aricka's Angels" and every penny from every piece goes to help a sweet young woman who suffers from Addison's Disease and has no job nor insurance to pay for her medicine. Helping people has always been more important to me than making money myself, because that's how my parents were. We lived comfortably, but not lavishly, because they gave all the money they could spare to church and charity, as well as donating time, energy, and transportation. They provided a really good example to me of how important it is to share God's blessings with others.
